1
00:01:59,893 --> 00:02:01,292
What am I working on?

2
00:02:01,893 --> 00:02:04,361
Something that will
change the world...

3
00:02:04,573 --> 00:02:06,245
...and human life as we know it.

4
00:02:06,613 --> 00:02:10,003
Change it a lot or just a bit?
Be more specific.

5
00:02:10,573 --> 00:02:13,041
You want me to be more
specific here with...

6
00:02:13,253 --> 00:02:16,529
...half the scientific
community eavesdropping?

7
00:02:17,173 --> 00:02:18,208
Where else?

8
00:02:19,933 --> 00:02:22,686
You could come back to my lab.

9
00:02:23,613 --> 00:02:25,126
I'll make cappuccino.

10
00:02:25,333 --> 00:02:27,369
I have a Faema of my own.

11
00:02:27,573 --> 00:02:30,212
It's not the dilettante's
plastic model.

12
00:02:30,493 --> 00:02:34,566
It's a restaurant espresso machine
with an eagle on top.

13
00:02:35,533 --> 00:02:38,001
Somehow I get the feeling
you don't get out much.

14
00:02:38,333 --> 00:02:41,405
- You can tell that?
- Yes.

15
00:02:51,013 --> 00:02:54,085
You're making a mistake.
I think you really want to talk to me.

16
00:02:54,373 --> 00:02:57,171
Sorry. I have three other interviews
before this party is over.

17
00:02:57,413 --> 00:02:59,927
But they don't have something
that will change the world.

18
00:03:00,373 --> 00:03:01,442
They say they do.

19
00:03:02,773 --> 00:03:04,286
Yeah but they're lying.

20
00:03:04,773 --> 00:03:05,842
I'm not.

21
00:03:11,813 --> 00:03:12,962
Are you sick?

22
00:03:13,613 --> 00:03:16,207
No... Sure.

23
00:03:16,733 --> 00:03:18,883
You're not a very good drunk.

24
00:03:19,933 --> 00:03:22,083
No, I'm always like this.
It's the...

25
00:03:22,813 --> 00:03:27,523
...motion sickness. When I was a kid,
I puked on my tricycle.

26
00:03:29,013 --> 00:03:30,571
I hate vehicles.

27
00:03:30,773 --> 00:03:32,286
Should I drive slowly?

28
00:03:32,533 --> 00:03:34,967
No. Turn left.
We're almost there.

29
00:03:51,853 --> 00:03:52,842
This is it?

30
00:03:53,173 --> 00:03:56,483
It's cleaner on the inside.

31
00:04:05,773 --> 00:04:07,001
Please.

32
00:04:36,413 --> 00:04:39,246
Listen.
Maybe this is a bad idea.

33
00:04:40,413 --> 00:04:41,971
Too late.

34
00:04:42,533 --> 00:04:46,003
You've already seen them.
You can't leave here alive.

35
00:04:48,933 --> 00:04:50,127
I haven't seen anything.

36
00:04:51,613 --> 00:04:52,762
Those.

37
00:04:58,333 --> 00:05:00,449
Designer phone booths.

38
00:05:00,653 --> 00:05:02,564
Very cute.

39
00:05:03,573 --> 00:05:06,645
I bet you have a really neat
jukebox in here too.

40
00:05:06,933 --> 00:05:08,161
Over there?

41
00:05:08,893 --> 00:05:10,042
No.

42
00:05:12,293 --> 00:05:14,443
No.
This is the...

43
00:05:15,373 --> 00:05:19,332
...prototype of those.
The first one I had made.

44
00:05:19,933 --> 00:05:23,767
It works, but it's clunky.

45
00:05:35,813 --> 00:05:37,531
I call them telepods.

46
00:05:38,533 --> 00:05:40,171
They're controlled by this.

47
00:05:40,813 --> 00:05:42,690
Thank God for that.

48
00:05:44,133 --> 00:05:47,091
So, what do they do?
The phones booths?

49
00:05:47,293 --> 00:05:48,282
Telepods.

50
00:05:52,773 --> 00:05:55,970
Okay, I need an object. Um.

51
00:05:58,173 --> 00:06:00,528
Do you have something that is...

52
00:06:01,173 --> 00:06:04,165
...personal I can use?
Something uniquely you?

53
00:06:04,893 --> 00:06:06,451
An item of clothing or jewelry?

54
00:06:07,413 --> 00:06:08,528
You kidding?

55
00:06:08,813 --> 00:06:10,087
No, I'm serious.

56
00:06:13,613 --> 00:06:16,252
Okay. Here it goes.

57
00:06:29,933 --> 00:06:30,922
Mm-hm.

58
00:06:34,453 --> 00:06:36,205
- I don't wear jewelry.
- Mm-hm.

59
00:06:43,133 --> 00:06:44,805
It's nice.

60
00:06:57,493 --> 00:06:59,643
Brundle, Seth.

61
00:07:12,933 --> 00:07:14,571
(BRUNDLE WHISPERS)

62
00:07:18,253 --> 00:07:19,606
Watch the stocking.

63
00:07:48,133 --> 00:07:49,088
Well?

64
00:07:50,413 --> 00:07:51,607
Great.

65
00:07:52,093 --> 00:07:55,881
A giant microwave oven. I'm glad
I didn't give you my Rolex.

66
00:07:56,093 --> 00:07:57,287
If I had a Rolex.

67
00:07:57,493 --> 00:07:59,563
You're missing the point.
Look.

68
00:08:07,213 --> 00:08:08,566
Teleportation?

69
00:08:10,333 --> 00:08:11,766
Please.

70
00:08:26,973 --> 00:08:28,531
Wait a minute.

71
00:08:30,013 --> 00:08:31,241
Is that a hologram?

72
00:08:31,773 --> 00:08:34,970
- Where's my stocking?
- That's it.

73
00:08:36,133 --> 00:08:37,043
Pick it up.

74
00:08:49,413 --> 00:08:51,324
I don't get it.

75
00:08:52,173 --> 00:08:53,242
What happened?

76
00:08:53,453 --> 00:08:55,887
You get it but you can't handle it.

77
00:08:57,213 --> 00:09:00,842
Your stocking has just
been teleported...

78
00:09:01,213 --> 00:09:04,410
...from one pod to another.

79
00:09:04,613 --> 00:09:07,366
Disintegrated there
and reintegrated there.

80
00:09:08,093 --> 00:09:09,128
Sort of.

81
00:09:10,253 --> 00:09:12,721
It will change the world
as we know it, right?

82
00:09:16,533 --> 00:09:17,886
Oh, no.

83
00:09:21,693 --> 00:09:23,172
This is incredible.

84
00:09:23,373 --> 00:09:25,091
It's not possible, is it?

85
00:09:25,533 --> 00:09:27,251
How have you kept this quiet?

86
00:09:28,093 --> 00:09:29,367
Please sit down.

87
00:09:29,773 --> 00:09:31,764
How could you do this alone?

88
00:09:32,413 --> 00:09:34,085
I don't work alone.

89
00:09:34,293 --> 00:09:36,682
There's stuff in there I don't
understand. I'm really a...

90
00:09:36,893 --> 00:09:38,531
...systems manager.
I farm out...

91
00:09:38,733 --> 00:09:41,725
...pieces to men more
brilliant than I. I say:

92
00:09:41,933 --> 00:09:46,609
"Design me a molecular analyzer,"
and they do. I just assemble it.

93
00:09:46,853 --> 00:09:49,447
None of them knows
what the project really is.

94
00:09:52,773 --> 00:09:56,129
And the money? Bartok
Science Industries financed this?

95
00:09:56,733 --> 00:09:59,486
But they leave me alone
because I'm not expensive.

96
00:09:59,893 --> 00:10:02,691
They know they'll own
whatever it is.

97
00:10:02,893 --> 00:10:04,372
You haven't told them?

98
00:10:04,733 --> 00:10:05,609
When I'm ready.

99
00:10:05,813 --> 00:10:06,882
(TAPE RECORDER BEEPS)

100
00:10:07,093 --> 00:10:08,526
Wait a second.

101
00:10:10,573 --> 00:10:11,483
What's that?

102
00:10:12,773 --> 00:10:14,172
To get the quotes right.

103
00:10:14,533 --> 00:10:16,763
Quotes? No.

104
00:10:16,973 --> 00:10:19,123
This was personal.
Don't write about it.

105
00:10:20,413 --> 00:10:22,768
What do you mean?
I'm a journalist.

106
00:10:23,013 --> 00:10:25,732
- Oh, no, no, no, no.
- You knew that.

107
00:10:26,813 --> 00:10:30,726
I made a mistake. I shouldn't
have shown you this. I'm very sorry.

108
00:10:30,933 --> 00:10:35,609
<i>Particle Magazine</i> sent me
to get a story.

109
00:10:35,813 --> 00:10:38,088
This is the most
exciting story ever.

110
00:10:38,293 --> 00:10:40,727
No. Absolutely not.
I must have that tape.

111
00:10:40,933 --> 00:10:42,366
- Please.
- You can't do that.

112
00:10:42,613 --> 00:10:43,841
Don't write a story.

113
00:10:44,053 --> 00:10:45,884
I'd never have told
this stuff to a journalist.

114
00:10:46,093 --> 00:10:49,529
- But you told it to me.
- I suppose I did but...

115
00:10:49,933 --> 00:10:51,571
- Sure did.
- Now wait a minute.

116
00:10:52,613 --> 00:10:54,808
Come here.
What about your stocking?

117
00:10:55,213 --> 00:10:57,090
Keep it for good luck.

118
00:11:07,693 --> 00:11:11,129
BRUNDLE: <i>I say: "Design me a
<i>molecular analyzer, " and they do.</i>

119
00:11:11,333 --> 00:11:12,368
<i>I just assemble it.</i>

120
00:11:12,733 --> 00:11:14,724
<i>None of them knows</i>
<i>what the project really is.</i>

121
00:11:17,693 --> 00:11:20,161
VERONICA: <i>And the money? Bartok</i>
<i>Science Industries financed this?</i>

122
00:11:20,413 --> 00:11:23,291
BRUNDLE: <i>But they leave me alone</i>
<i>because I'm not expensive.</i>

123
00:11:24,173 --> 00:11:26,562
<i>They know they'll own</i>
<i>whatever it is.</i>

124
00:11:27,893 --> 00:11:30,043
Well, that's it.

125
00:11:31,573 --> 00:11:32,608
What do you think?

126
00:11:33,333 --> 00:11:34,448
It's a joke.

127
00:11:34,653 --> 00:11:35,449
What?

128
00:11:35,653 --> 00:11:37,166
He's conning you.

129
00:11:37,413 --> 00:11:39,768
It's an old nightclub routine.
The two cabinets.

130
00:11:40,173 --> 00:11:41,162
You fell for it.

131
00:11:41,373 --> 00:11:42,567
(PHONE RINGS)

132
00:11:42,813 --> 00:11:45,088
- Wait. That was no...
- Are we having lunch?

133
00:11:45,573 --> 00:11:48,770
That was no nightclub routine.
I was there. I saw it.

134
00:11:51,253 --> 00:11:52,368
Yeah?

135
00:11:54,533 --> 00:11:55,727
Sure.

136
00:11:56,293 --> 00:11:57,726
Send him in.

137
00:11:58,973 --> 00:12:01,203
You must have made an impression.

138
00:12:01,573 --> 00:12:02,562
What do you mean?

139
00:12:03,133 --> 00:12:05,647
Your magician followed you here.

140
00:12:08,373 --> 00:12:11,251
I'm Stathis Borans,
editor of <i>Particle Magazine.</i>

141
00:12:11,453 --> 00:12:15,446
- Seth Brundle.
- I know who you are. Listen...

142
00:12:15,653 --> 00:12:18,929
...why don't you two use my office?
I've gotta run.

143
00:12:19,333 --> 00:12:22,370
If you plan to make anything
disappear, let me know.

144
00:12:22,613 --> 00:12:25,969
I have an assistant editor
who's outlived his usefulness.

145
00:12:30,733 --> 00:12:31,961
You didn't waste time.

146
00:12:32,813 --> 00:12:34,769
I'm not getting any younger.

147
00:12:37,133 --> 00:12:39,283
He wasn't impressed by your tape?

148
00:12:40,853 --> 00:12:42,332
He thinks you're a con man.

149
00:12:45,413 --> 00:12:46,323
Excellent.

150
00:12:46,533 --> 00:12:49,445
Yeah? Well, let's see what the people
at <i>Omni</i> think about it.

151
00:12:49,653 --> 00:12:51,848
No, no.
Listen, Veronica...

152
00:12:53,733 --> 00:12:56,167
I've come here to say one magic word.

153
00:12:57,453 --> 00:12:58,283
Yeah?

154
00:12:59,173 --> 00:13:00,208
Cheeseburger.

155
00:13:05,453 --> 00:13:07,569
I've been working alone too long.

156
00:13:09,173 --> 00:13:12,404
I have a strong urge
to talk about what I'm doing.

157
00:13:13,373 --> 00:13:16,046
But if this gets out now...

158
00:13:16,253 --> 00:13:18,164
...Veronica, it'll kill me.

159
00:13:18,813 --> 00:13:21,407
The Bartok people
and my colleagues will kill me.

160
00:13:22,373 --> 00:13:23,601
It's not ready yet.

161
00:13:23,853 --> 00:13:25,206
It works okay.

162
00:13:25,533 --> 00:13:27,683
No, something important's missing.

163
00:13:28,093 --> 00:13:29,048
Yeah?

164
00:13:30,293 --> 00:13:31,328
Yeah.

165
00:13:33,293 --> 00:13:34,203
What?

166
00:13:36,613 --> 00:13:39,411
I can only teleport inanimate objects.

167
00:13:42,173 --> 00:13:44,323
What happens when you
teleport living things?

168
00:13:46,013 --> 00:13:47,048
Not while we're eating.

169
00:13:47,813 --> 00:13:49,769
Can't be worse than this.

170
00:13:53,093 --> 00:13:55,653
You're not doing
a good job of convincing me.

171
00:13:55,853 --> 00:13:59,368
I think I should tell
the world about this now.

172
00:13:59,973 --> 00:14:01,565
You should tell it...

173
00:14:03,533 --> 00:14:05,922
...but not yet.
What do you have so far?

174
00:14:06,733 --> 00:14:08,166
Enough to make you nervous.

175
00:14:08,373 --> 00:14:11,729
Why not get more? Make me
your major project, a book.

176
00:14:11,933 --> 00:14:13,810
Not a magazine article.

177
00:14:14,013 --> 00:14:17,164
Follow me and my work,
day by day in detail.

178
00:14:17,813 --> 00:14:21,692
I have no life, so there's nothing
for you to interfere with.

179
00:14:21,893 --> 00:14:25,442
Research the background.
Cover the process.

180
00:14:26,613 --> 00:14:29,764
"The complete record of the most
earth-shattering invention ever.

181
00:14:30,013 --> 00:14:33,323
The one that ended
all concepts of transport...

182
00:14:33,533 --> 00:14:36,366
...of borders and frontiers,
of time and space."

183
00:14:38,893 --> 00:14:41,532
The book will end with me...

184
00:14:41,733 --> 00:14:45,043
...transporting myself
from one telepod to another.

185
00:14:45,253 --> 00:14:46,481
That's what's missing.

186
00:14:49,573 --> 00:14:50,926
Wait for me that long?

187
00:15:09,173 --> 00:15:10,526
(SHOWER RUNNING)

188
00:15:36,693 --> 00:15:38,604
What are you doing here?

189
00:15:39,013 --> 00:15:41,766
STATHIS: I was in the neighborhood.
Felt a bit scummy.

190
00:15:43,773 --> 00:15:45,172
Rough day.

191
00:15:48,213 --> 00:15:49,885
(FLUSHES TOILET)

192
00:15:50,133 --> 00:15:52,488
(STATHIS YELLS)

193
00:15:55,533 --> 00:15:56,886
How'd you get in?

194
00:15:58,333 --> 00:16:00,210
I have a key, remember?

195
00:16:00,613 --> 00:16:01,728
You gave it to me.

196
00:16:02,173 --> 00:16:03,652
I should've changed the lock.

197
00:16:05,013 --> 00:16:05,923
You didn't.

198
00:16:06,773 --> 00:16:08,411
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

199
00:16:09,773 --> 00:16:13,243
That's because unconsciously...

200
00:16:14,933 --> 00:16:18,084
...you still want me to come back,
move in again.

201
00:16:18,373 --> 00:16:19,442
No.

202
00:16:20,133 --> 00:16:24,445
That's because, consciously,
I'm lazy and disorganized.

203
00:16:29,653 --> 00:16:31,325
Your new playmate's interesting.

204
00:16:31,533 --> 00:16:32,852
What playmate?

205
00:16:33,213 --> 00:16:34,851
The nightclub act.

206
00:16:36,653 --> 00:16:37,847
Brundle.

207
00:16:39,093 --> 00:16:41,163
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

208
00:16:42,773 --> 00:16:46,163
I was wrong.
He's really quite brilliant.

209
00:16:47,773 --> 00:16:51,368
He led the F32 team.
Remember that?

210
00:16:52,573 --> 00:16:55,531
An inch away from the
Nobel Prize for physics.

211
00:16:56,013 --> 00:16:58,208
He was only 20 at the time.

212
00:16:58,813 --> 00:17:02,567
I'm not going to do Brundle.
Maybe the <i>Psychology Today</i> gig.

213
00:17:03,173 --> 00:17:04,288
That's not like you.

214
00:17:06,013 --> 00:17:08,163
Are you getting out or am I?

215
00:17:09,813 --> 00:17:13,283
I'll go. Shall I return later
and tuck you in?

216
00:17:13,893 --> 00:17:15,724
No. Key.

217
00:17:17,693 --> 00:17:19,206
I'll keep it...

218
00:17:20,173 --> 00:17:21,492
...for old time's sake.

219
00:17:23,653 --> 00:17:25,769
You're a petty schmuck.

220
00:17:46,013 --> 00:17:48,322
Initiate in 5 seconds.

221
00:18:47,773 --> 00:18:50,207
(SQUEALS)

222
00:19:05,333 --> 00:19:07,563
I've got to do this, Seth.

223
00:19:07,813 --> 00:19:09,644
Talk to the tape.
Get in the habit.

224
00:19:09,973 --> 00:19:11,691
The world will want to know
what you're thinking.

225
00:19:11,893 --> 00:19:13,770
"Fuck" is what I'm thinking!

226
00:19:14,253 --> 00:19:15,402
Good.

227
00:19:15,613 --> 00:19:18,002
The world will want to know that.

228
00:19:19,413 --> 00:19:21,483
What else?
Why didn't it work?

229
00:19:22,213 --> 00:19:25,330
I think it turned the baboon
inside out.

230
00:19:28,493 --> 00:19:29,528
Why?

231
00:19:30,893 --> 00:19:34,966
It can't deal with the flesh,
only inanimate objects.

232
00:19:37,733 --> 00:19:39,246
It must be my fault.

233
00:19:40,133 --> 00:19:41,043
Why?

234
00:19:43,533 --> 00:19:46,286
Computers only know
what you tell them.

235
00:19:47,813 --> 00:19:51,169
I don't know enough about the flesh.
I have to learn.

236
00:19:55,613 --> 00:19:57,763
I don't want to talk now.

237
00:20:16,373 --> 00:20:18,364
Do you ever change your clothes?

238
00:20:19,733 --> 00:20:21,132
What?

239
00:20:21,893 --> 00:20:24,771
You're always wearing
the same clothes.

240
00:20:27,973 --> 00:20:32,171
No, these are clean.
I change my clothes every day.

241
00:20:41,093 --> 00:20:43,402
Five sets of exactly the same clothes?

242
00:20:44,013 --> 00:20:45,048
Learned it from Einstein.

243
00:20:46,413 --> 00:20:47,926
This way I don't have to...

244
00:20:48,133 --> 00:20:52,331
...expend any thought on what to wear.
I grab the next set on the rack.

245
00:20:58,733 --> 00:21:02,408
I bought some steaks.
Can I make you one?

246
00:21:03,453 --> 00:21:04,568
We could go out.

247
00:21:05,773 --> 00:21:06,888
Cheeseburger?

248
00:21:10,133 --> 00:21:13,364
No, we don't have to go there.

249
00:21:21,613 --> 00:21:24,650
You're very cute. You know that?

250
00:21:25,533 --> 00:21:26,568
Am I?

251
00:21:44,453 --> 00:21:46,523
(KISSING)

252
00:22:03,893 --> 00:22:04,803
Ew. Ow.

253
00:22:05,013 --> 00:22:06,605
- What happened?
- On my back. Ow.

254
00:22:08,693 --> 00:22:11,002
Oh, God,
something's stuck to your back.

255
00:22:11,213 --> 00:22:13,044
Pull it off.

256
00:22:15,413 --> 00:22:18,371
VERONICA: Oh, ew.
BRUNDLE: Ow.

257
00:22:20,973 --> 00:22:22,406
Sorry.

258
00:22:24,133 --> 00:22:26,044
I wondered where this was.

259
00:22:26,253 --> 00:22:29,768
- Do you have any disinfectant?
- No, that's okay.

260
00:22:29,973 --> 00:22:31,611
I'll kiss it for you.

261
